segments.text: Hello, kitty, kitty, kitty.
Hello, kitty, kitty, kitty.
I'm going to get you to talk to me.
When this was all in, when, during the Depression, and when I say Depression, that was back in the good old days.
I know.
You had to do without your meat, your sweets, and your sugar, and all that kind of stuff.
Your flour.
What?
And you, well, um,
Her mother always fixed graham biscuits for Uncle Sam, and she actually didn't know any different, which is great.
And she thought everybody ate them.
But they didn't.
And she'd come to our house, and we'd have cornbread.
And she didn't know what it was.
But old Lennon would say, I want some more.
And we'd have a mania night.
All we'd have for supper would be cornbread and what we call Friday gravy.
And by the way, we ate it.
And a glass of milk, whether it would be clabber or sweet milk or buttermilk.
We had that milk.
But we had a very humble home.
but one that I wouldn't trade for all the modern ones in the world.
Mother sat at the foot of the table and Daddy at the head.
And we had a bench.
In those days, children sat on benches.
And we all three sat on one bench, right down this way.
And the other part of the table was pushed up against the wall.
So we'd have more room in the dining room.

i was the first one and then next was margaret and james was next to mother he was the baby and she would see well our plates were set by the side of dads and our knife and fork and spoon and napkin and our napkin ring now we had napkin rings and our napkins our napkins
Nine times out of ten were made out of flour sacks.
But we had a napkin.
It wasn't made out of an old shirt tail that hadn't wore out.
But we had a napkin.
We took that napkin and we sat down and we unfolded it and put it in our lap.
And we put our hands down in our lap.
And our father asked the blessing.
And then he served our plate and we passed it down.
James Ely was served first, and then Margaret.
I mean, mother was served first, and then James, and then Margaret and me.
I was the last one, and my dad was next to last to be served.
No one picked up a fork and started to dive in until everyone was served.
And then my father would always say, bless this food, God, to the nourishment of our body and to our soul, and help us
to love our fellow man more dearly each day.
That was just clockwork.
That's beautiful.
He'd already asked the blessing, but the food was to be blessed for the nourishment of our body and that we would live to love our fellow man.
That's beautiful.
To me, I wouldn't take for it.
And then at night when we'd get ready for bed,
It wasn't, go on, go to bed.
Get your things and get to bed.
Get out of here.
I want to read or I want to listen.
No.
Mother would sit in that old chair.
I gave the chair to Mark.
But anyway, it was that old rocking chair.
And she'd be sitting in it.
And she'd say, we always had to hang our nightclothes.
We had no closets on the nail behind the door in our room.
So we'd go in there.
and get our clothes off of the nail and dress in our room, hang our clothes that we wore up on this nail that we took our gown off of.
It wouldn't be laying on the floor, but they'd be hanging up behind that door, because that room was going to be straight.
And we'd come back into Mama's room, and she would gather us around her knee.
And always, I would be on the right, Margaret in the middle, and James on the left.
And she'd put her hand on each one of us as we said our prayers.
And it was now I lay me down to sleep.
But it was a real prayer.
And we would always, it didn't make any difference how bad we'd been that day and how many whippings we'd got.
Help me to be a better girl tomorrow.
Help me to understand and mind my parents.
That was ritualistic.
That was ritualistic.
Help me to mind my parents.
Honor thy father and thy mother that the days may be long upon the earth which the Lord thy God giveth thee.
That was ritualistic.
And that's the reason I don't understand children
But it's home.
It reverts back to home.
And lots of times, we'd sing.
We'd sit around, and we'd sing songs.
And she would read the Bible and tell us stories.
Or she'd read a good story out of a lady's home journal.
Well, we had a pictorial review.
and a ladies home journal.
Well, the pictorial review come earlier, and we got ladies home journal much later.
And of course, we got a weekly newspaper.
San Antonio Express was a weekly newspaper.
And we didn't get mail here but three times a week.
That's the main thing.
And we take what they call a little old newspaper that was printed in Chicago called The Grit.
And it's still in publication.
And it has a lot of good reading in it today.
Now, don't forget that.
Lots of good reading in today.
And that would come in our San Antonio Express weekly.
Our weekly.
No telephone, no radios, and all we got was by word or mouth from neighbors.
That system of telling who's done what, when, and how it's going.
And come by to see you.
And I think, well, there was a heap of living in those days.
There really was.
We had an old piano.
And when I won't tell you right now, all of us would sit down and take our hand at it, whether we played good or whether we didn't.
We enjoyed it.
And that's what counts.
My mother and father had the most beautiful voices together that ever was.
Mother sang soprano and daddy sang tenor.
And mother was a pretty woman.
And my daddy was.
a handsome man.
And I guess love makes them look prettier.
I guess the deep feeling that you have and the respect you have for your parents, they just look different to you than to anybody else.
I don't know, Mother just looked like a queen every time she stepped out.
And she was so erect in her walk and so portly.
And she held herself so well.
She wasn't slovenly in her walk.
And her manner of dress was always so very, very neat.
Now the difference in the two women and my mother and Lennon's mother
Lennon's mother was never needing her clothes.
Lennon was just exactly like her.
God bless him.
His shirt tail would be out somewhere.
And he had nice clothes and everything.
And he could, if you just catch him just right before he got on the stage, just push him on there and see that he's ruined perfect.
He'd be all right.
But by the time he got off of it, there'd be something wrong.
Really?
Every time.
But that's just the way with people.
It is.
You know, I think it's, I think that.
And I think a lot of that rubbed off on me.
I think so.
Well, eat all you want out of it.
I'm hungry for good food.
You're hungry for food.
Well, that's great.
Well, it's like, I agree there's nothing like the kind of life that I, and I say we had here, as you know I had, a great part of what you're talking about in my home before my mother died.
We came from this out part of the country into Austin.
And I had, as you say, the napkins made out of shirt tails or whatever was available and the rugs that everybody just, if you couldn't pass it down anymore, it ended up being ripped up for a rag rug.
Well, my goodness, I used to help my mother dye rugs and, I mean, rags, make rugs out of.
Yeah.
And when we were at the ranch, we had a...
excuse me, 14 by 16 bedroom.
Two double beds in it and a big stove, heater.
And that's where we, and a cot.
And we all slept in there because it's so cold.
And we had single wall.
Oh, that single wall construction.
Absolutely.
Papa put a big old green stick of wood in that heater or an old cedar log and get up and fire it up again in the night and kept it warm.
And we kept warm.
And we'd sleep in there.
And Mama made a rug to cover that whole room and made it on a loom over here at Blanco.
out of old rags.
Old rags.
And they were dyed in different colors, and she made striping.
Yeah.
And she used a lot of red, and it was pretty.
Those kinds of things, if women had to do them today, they just wouldn't be able to handle a lot.
No, they wouldn't do it.
Boy, we knew better than to spill anything, get anything on that rug.
Now, that was something.
Mm-hmm.
The survival of the family depended on the woman in most cases as far as being sure that everything was done.
It wasn't a part of life.
It wasn't, I hate to say this, a lot of people would disagree, but it wasn't an ERA fight between husband and wife.
It was if one didn't do her share or his share, it wasn't done.
And they're both laborious tasks.
A lot of labor combined between both people to simply survive back then.
Now, I want to tell you right now, I've seen my mother sit on a cultivator all day long and cook dinner.
And when she'd go to the house to cook dinner, I'd get through hoeing at the end, and I'd get on the cultivator.
And I'd make the rounds and come back.
And then she'd come back and take it over.
That cultivator didn't stop.
Do you think today that you'd take a seven-year-old girl and put her on a cultivator driving a span of mules?
Why?
Oh, she'd get killed if something happened.
Yeah.
Yeah.
But it wasn't that way.
You had to do it to get the job done again.
Why?
Good night.
Well, Ava, I think that that's the thing that I want people to hear about.
Just keep going and tell me everything you can remember of value to you.
Those things are worth more to me than anything that I can think of.
Oh, of course.
Now, I'm glad that we live in a time that the girls and the women didn't have to do it.
But many a time...

uh i drive four mules to a triple disc plow now you didn't have many crippled this plow in those days you had double discs but very few cripples yeah that's a hard one and that was that was a hard one to pull in a big one but we had um grandpa and uncle buddy and my daddy bought one together yeah and that's the way we we would share well all right tom you do yours first and then
Jay, you take it.
And then they'd all fly in and help Grandpa Chapman because he was older and no one to help him at that time.
And the men would help.
But Daddy would never let that thing stop.
I would plow
Margaret would plow, Mama would plow, and he would plow.
My daddy had sciatic rheumatism and was to the point where he couldn't walk at all at one time.
And they say it was from riding on that hard steel plow and jolting it and hurting it, whether it was or whether it wasn't.
He and Mother made a cushion, but they didn't help.
He just had sciatic nerve trouble and just couldn't do it.
But anyway, we all worked at it.
I wouldn't take for knowing how to drive up.
for mules.
It's something that you understand and something that's worth something.
Now, no, it isn't worth anything.
It may be, if things keep going like they're going, we may be back in the same old hill.
My grandfather used to say that.
My grandfather said that the day would come that we'd have everything.
Come in!
That it would all...
Turn right around.
We're doing some homework.
The main thing that I appreciate my parents as much or more than anything was the routine that we had.
Of course, we lived so far and had to ride the school horseback.
Right.
And open gates.
But it wasn't on until we...
learn to open gates by making a horse ride up to the gate and reaching over and undoing it and staying on the horse and closing the gate.
But the responsibility of caring for that horse, get up and feed that horse before breakfast,
And then the minute that breakfast was over, you go saddle that horse and bring it down here and tie it to the fence.
Then put on your school clothes and mother will have your lunch ready and beat it.
You get ready for school.
When I say beat it, you didn't have any time to do anything.
But every night you shucked that corn and you nubbed it.
When I say nub it, you took every bit of it.
off of the end of the ears, and you put it over here in a bucket, and you'd throw it out to the chickens.
If there was any good there, they'd get it, and if it wasn't, it would make good manure.
So out it went outside.
But you shucked that corn at night for your hogs, your chickens, your turkeys, and your horse, and you put it in a box, but you nubbed every bit of it.
You didn't feed a hog a bunch of old smutty corn and stuff like that.
You fed him good stuff.
And we had a grinder that you put your corn in, and they'd take it off of the cob and you'd grind it.
You'd stack those cobs in a neat stack.
Every night you took six cobs into the house.
One of them you put in a can that had a little bit of kerosene in it that you would put in to start the fire the next morning.
And then you used three or four, as Kenley liked to, under your wood, split wood, to start your fire.
But that was routine, and if that wasn't done,
then mother and dad called you in and you really got a good little spanking.
And I mean, it was bridal reins and it hurt.
And you knew better.
And you understood that it was something that you had to do.
And you milked the cows, you gathered the eggs, you shut the chickens up,
Then you came in, washed your hands, ate your supper, and got your lessons.
It wasn't come in and sit down and watch television and play.
No, sir.
There was work to do.
And you did it.
And then, well, all me alive, I was milking cows when I was five years old.
And I can prove that by anybody that knows me in this country.
Show me a five-year-old kid they're getting a cow pen now with a bunch of cows.
That's right.
They're scared they're going to get stepped on.
They're afraid, and they don't trust their children.
They give them no responsibility.
And what is wrong?
Adults don't trust children.
What's wrong with the world today is they have no confidence in their children.
Oh, I don't want him to have to work like I did.
Listen, that's wrong.
He needs that responsibility.
He needs to know where that dollar came from.
He needs to understand that he doesn't grow on trees.
How many times have I come to town on Saturday and
feed cotton, bales of cotton up, gin down here.
Rub that old gin thing around in a bale of cotton.
Let it suck it up.
Just a kid.
Oh, no.
Oh, that thing had sucked that child up.
It had hurt it.
It had killed it.
It had knocked it down.
That was the way it was.
That was survival.
That was life.
That was life.
That was life.
and pick up peach seeds and take them to town and sell them.
Wash medicine bottles and take them to the drug store and sell them.
For a penny.
That's right.
That's the way we'd get our spending money.
Really?
Would a kid do that today?
No.
He wouldn't pick up peach seeds and wash them off and put them in a box and go sell them.
No.
That's right.
No, they wouldn't.
No, they wouldn't.
They may pick up a beer can.
They may pick up a soda water can, but we didn't even have soda water.
Right.
That's valuable to me, Ava.
I agree with times have changed so much, and kids are cheated.
Children are really cheated out of the responsibility that they could assume when they're little bitty and growing.
You know, they could be doing things that make them pleased with themselves.
Children are cheated in more ways than one.
It's true.
I was brought up in a time and the age that little folks were seen and not heard.
But we had ears and we listened.
And we learned.
We learned.
We were not sent to our room unless we misbehaved and didn't listen while they were talking.
Then we were sent to our room.
But we could sit there, and I'm telling you, I wasn't 12 years old, and I know it.
And I would sit in the room and listen to Uncle Clarence Martin, who was district judge and district prosecuting attorney and all that for this country.
And Uncle Sam was in the legislature.
And my daddy was just a rancher.
But they would talk over politics of what's happening in the world.
As I said, we had no newspaper.
But they were in the towns where they could get the news.
Well, I knew who was governor.
I knew who was our congressman.
I will grant you, right today, you can walk downtown and pick out any bunch of kids you want to, unless they're in high school.
They couldn't tell you who was even governor of Texas or who was president.
They care less.
That's true.
But they can tell you what Mickey Mouse is doing.
Yeah, that's true.
What Michael Jackson's doing.
That's what they can tell you.
Yes.
And their greatest ambition in life is to get to sin.
That's right.
Instead of valuing their own individual self,
and growing because they know what it means to learn and grow.
They haven't been taught.
Kids haven't been taught how to learn and grow.
And the thing I can remember, I guess, the most at that particular time was the greatest event and joy that I had was when Teddy Roosevelt came through Austin with his Rough Riders going to
going to the border.
Yeah.
Do you know that my daddy and Uncle Sam loaded us up in an old Model T car?
Took us five hours to go from here to Austin in that Model T. And every creek we stopped, we had to fill it up with water.
It'd boil out.
It'd be so hot.
The roads were so rough.
No pavement.
Not even a good wagon road, hardly.
And jolt, oh, that's the roughest riding thing.
You really needed spurs to stay in it.
But we got there, and...
We stayed at the Cabinets House.
The Cabinets, yes.
You know where that is.
That's right.
We stayed at the Cabinets House.
And I believe that that avenue was the most beautiful thing I ever saw in my life.
You know, the post used to go right up the center of the street and had the lights in a diamond shape.
And they lit them up.
And I had never seen electric lights like that.
Oh, yeah.
All the lights that I had ever seen had been a carbide light that was up at Uncle Clarence's, other than a kerosene light like we had never seen electric light.
I didn't know what one looked like.
And when I saw those beautiful lights, I just stopped.

still just dead still and I asked my daddy what they were because they were in colors red white and blue and he told me now you can imagine what what a great big old girl I thought about first time she'd ever seen electric yeah
And I thought that was the most wonderful thing that ever was.
Well, Uncle Sam took us to the Capitol, showed us where his seat was, showed us the chamber and the legislature, all about it, explained it to us.
And we knew, of course.
come back.
And I'm telling you, Uncle Clarence Martin then bought us all a pair of new shoes.
And it's patent leather.
I'll tell you, what was that?
Well, it's a Jew store there on 6th Street.
Not Scarborough's, was it?
No, not Scarborough's.
Scarborough's was on the Avenue then.
Oh, on 6th Street.
Oh, Gilliman's.
Gilliman's.
Okay, I've seen that one.
Yeah, Gilliman's on Fifth Street.
And we went in there, and just above Gilliman was Joe Cohen, a jeweler.
Right.
And he bought Margaret and I a little ring, and James, Eddie, and Lyndon a ring.
Now, I don't know why in the world Rebecca and Joseph are at Lyndon's sister's.
I think because Aunt Rebecca didn't want them to go, but we went to Lyndon.
And I don't really know, but they never did associate with us in doing things like that.
And he bought us all a little ring at Joe Cohen's.
Yeah, that's the prettiest thing he ever looked at.
But anyway, he bought us patent leather shoes.
And mine was black with white tops.
And Marv's was black with red tops, kid's skin tops.
And we'd walk up and down that pavement.
And Lennon's was black patent leather with, well, they were lace shoes.
Uh-huh.
Not worthy or worthy button.
I believe his is button.
I believe his is button shoes.
I believe James Ealy's is button.
They both rather have the buttons than the lace because they come undone.
And I believe they both had button shoes.
Well, anyway, we walked on up to...
What was that big old drugstore up there?
Oh.
Oh.
Just sure look.
I know.
It was an old keep.
Not King's.
Well, I can't think of it right now, but anyway.
Where was it about a...
Up above Scarborough.
Up above, yeah, I know.
That great big drugstore.
Great big drugstore.
And we went up there and stayed at this drugstore for a while.
And he told the man he was going to go see something, somebody on up further.
And he went to the counter and he says, feed those kids all the ice cream or anything they want to drink and let them sit here.
Well, boy, we filled up.
Don't think we didn't.
We ate ice cream and Lennon got a banana split.
Of course, we'd never seen a banana split and didn't know what one was like.
And oh my goodness, when they brought that out to Lennon, well, I'll never forget.
He ate every bit of it, but he'd already eaten a big bowl of ice cream.
And poor little fella really got sick.
He just got too...
much and it was too hot a day and he really got sick and he said well and oh and he says now i'm going down and then i'll tom will pick you up that is my daddy will pick you up and so daddy
came by and picked us up.
And he said, well, I want to go down to Leonard E.'s wagon yard and see how much they're paying for turkeys and chickens, because I've got to bring them down next week or two to market.
And so we walked on from wherever this drug store was, which is way up above Scarborough's and is up above Woolworth's.
Any other time I could think of.
I know.
I can see it from the pictures I remember.
But I can't tell you.
But anyway, and women say, well.
It's a good history.
